  "text": "In addition, d max and D max are supposed to be known in order to apply this criterion but they are not used in the controller design. Theorem 1 and equations (26) and (27) show that the design of a Lipschitz controller with the new reconstructed predictionXp given by [CITATION_1] leads to a smaller error bound than designing a controller with the standard reconstructed prediction [CITATION_2] . Consequently, the new predictive scheme is said to better attenuate the disturbances than the standard one. Note that the criterion (28) is the same as in [CITATION_3] : it is independent of the observer choice. Indeed, the same observer is designed in both cases: it means that whatever the observer (robust, finite time), (28) will remain unchanged. The result holds for a wide class of functions f so it gives the possibility to robustly stabilizê Xp at zero. However, even ifXp converges to zero, there are inevitable errors in (25) when the perturbation is timevarying:",
